Answer: Yes, it is possible to make your code dynamic and process files with varying columns. You can use the `Iterator.next()` method to iterate over the records in the CSV file. For each record, you can create a new `Employee` object and set its properties based on the values in the record. The number of properties (columns) in the record is determined dynamically.

Here is an example of how you can modify your code:

```java
private static List<Employee> parseCSVFileAsList() throws IOException {
    CSVReader reader = new CSVReader(new FileReader("employees.csv"), ',');
    List<Employee> emps = new ArrayList<Employee>();
    Iterator<String[]> iterator = reader.iterator();
    // skip header row
    iterator.next();
    while(iterator.hasNext()){
        String[] record = iterator.next();
        Employee emp = new Employee();
        for (int i = 0; i < record.length; i++) {
            switch (i) {
                case 0:
                    emp.setId(record[i]);
                    break;
                case 1:
                    emp.setName(record[i]);
                    break;
                case 2:
                    emp.setRole(record[i]);
                    break;
                case 3:
                    emp.setSalary(record[i]);
                    break;
                // Add more cases for additional columns
            }
        }
        emps.add(emp);
    }
    reader.close();
    return emps;
}
```

